ero entry in the first row, so it is% in echelon form. There are two pivot columns in $A$, so $r(A)=2$. \par Next, we will look at $A$ from the perspective of rows. Note that there % are two pivot rows in $A$. In fact, the number of pivot columns should equal % the number of pivot rows for any matrix. \par It is not yet apparent how the notion of rank is useful. Can the rank of% a matrix help us in our goal of determining solutions to a system of linear % equations? \par \par First, let us address a question. How can the dimensions of the % matrix affect the possible value of its rank? \par \@@section{paragraph}{Sx2.SS0.SSS0.Px1}{}{}{}{Question:}What is the % maximum possible value of $r(A)$ if $A$ is a matrix of size $4	imes 6$? \par Let us try to consider a general $4	imes 6$ matrix, and see what can % happen after reducing it to row echelon form, since that will determine its % rank. \par It is clear that we may obtain four pivots if the row echelon form turns% out like so: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{bmatrix}*&*&*&*&*&*\ *&*&*&*&*&*\ *&*&*&*&*&*\ *&*&*&*&*&*\end{bmatrix}	o egin{bmatrix} lacksquare&*&*&*&*&*\ 0& lacksquare&*&*&*&*\ 0&0& lacksquare&*&*&*\ 0&0&0& lacksquare&\square&*\end{bmatrix}$&$$&$\displaystyle\left\{ egin{% aligned}\displaystyle*&&\displaystyle	ext{any number}\ \displaystyle lacksquare&&\displaystyle	ext{non-zero}\ \displaystyle 0&&\displaystyle	ext{zero}\end{aligned}ight.$ And we see that there is no way to obtain a fifth pivot -- any non-zero entry % besides the already-existing pivots will not be a leading non-zero entry, and % thus not be a pivot. \par \@@section{paragraph}{Sx2.SS0.SSS0.Px2}{}{}{}{Question:}What if $A$ is $6% 	imes 4$? \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{bmatrix}*&*&*&*\ *&*&*&*\ *&*&*&*\ *&*&*&*\ *&*&*&*\ *&*&*&*\end{bmatrix}$ Since we can at most obtain one pivot per column, we are still limited to at % most four pivots. Thus the maximum rank is still $4$. \par It still remains to be seen how the notion of rank can be useful in % solving a system. \par \vspace{1cm} \par Consider the following system: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left\{ egin{aligned}\displaystyle x+2y-3z&% \displaystyle=1\ \displaystyle x-y+z&\displaystyle=0\ \displaystyle 3x+3y-5z&\displaystyle=3\end{aligned}ight.$ and suppose that we wish to find the number of solutions of the system and % what they are. \par First, we convert the augmented matrix of the system to row echelon form% : \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rrr|r]1&2&-3&1\ 1&-1&1&0\ 3&3&-5&3\end{matrix}ight]\xrightarrow[-3R_{1}+R_{3}]{-R_{1}+R_{2}}\left[%  egin{matrix}[rrr|r]1&2&-3&1\ 0&-3&4&-1\ 0&-3&4&0\end{matrix}ight]\xrightarrow[]{-R_{2}+R_{3}}\left[ egin{matrix}[% rrr|r]1&2&-3&1\ 0&-3&4&-1\ 0&0&0&1\end{matrix}ight]$ We find that the augmented matrix has three pivots. Then the entire matrix has% rank $3$. \par The last row says that $0=1$. Thus the system is inconsistent. \par It is important to distinguish between the rank of the entire augmented % matrix and the rank of the coefficient matrix. Note that in this example the % augmented matrix has rank $3$ whereas the coefficient matrix has rank $2$. \par Let us re-examine the system in a slightly different way. We will % introduce the parameter $k$: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left\{ egin{aligned}\displaystyle x+2y-3z&% \displaystyle=1\ \displaystyle x-y+z&\displaystyle=0\ \displaystyle 3x+3y-5z&\displaystyle=\mathbf{k}\end{aligned}ight.$ Find those values of $k$ for which the system is consistent. \par One important thing to note is that changing values in the constant % column really does not have an effect on the row reduction operations. Only % the values in the constant column will change in the intermediate (and final) % steps. \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rrr|c]1&2&-3&1\ 1&-1&1&0\ 3&3&-5&\mathbf{k}\end{matrix}ight]\xrightarrow[-3R_{1}+R_{3}]{-R_{1}+R_{2}}% \left[ egin{matrix}[rrr|c]1&2&-3&1\ 0&-3&4&-1\ 0&-3&4&\mathbf{k-3}\end{matrix}ight]\xrightarrow[]{-R_{2}+R_{3}}\left[ egin% {matrix}[rrr|c]1&2&-3&1\ 0&-3&4&-1\ 0&0&0&\mathbf{k-2}\end{matrix}ight]$ \par Recall what we have discussed previously: for consistency we cannot have% a pivot appearing in the last column of the augmented matrix. \par The only way this can happen is if $k-2=0$ so that it is not a pivot. % Then $k=2$ for the system to be consistent. \par \@@section{paragraph}{Sx2.SS0.SSS0.Px3}{}{}{}{Question:}For $k=2$, find % the number of solutions. \par For $k=2$, the augmented matrix becomes \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rrr|r]{\color{red} oxed@math{{% \color{black}1}}}&2&-3&1\ 0&{\color{red} oxed@math{{\color{black}-3}}}&4&-1\ 0&0&0&0\end{matrix}ight]$ which is in echelon form. Let us call the coefficient matrix $A$. Then \par The number of pivot columns $=r(A)=2$. \par The number of free columns is $3-r(A)=1$. \par Because we are considering only the coefficient matrix and there is a % free column, this means the system has a free variable. \par We have shown that the system is consistent in this case, so it has at % least one solution. Since there is a free variable, there are in fact % infinitely many solutions. Note that if the system were inconsistent, then % there would be no solutions rather than infinitely many solutions. \par Note that we did not have to solve the system to determine the number of% solutions that it has! \par \par \par Consider the following matrix: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[ccccc|c]1&0&0&0&0&s\ 0&0&1&0&1&t\ 0&0&0&1&0&u\end{matrix}ight]$ Is the system consistent for all $s,t,u$? How many solutions are there? \par Let us again call the coefficient matrix of the augmented matrix $A$. \par Because of the placement of the $1$'s in the coefficient matrix, none of% $s,t,u$ can become pivots for any values they may take on. They will never % become leading non-zero entries, and thus never be pivots. This also tells us % that a pivot will never enter the constant vector. \par Thus, the system will always be consistent and $r(A)=3$ for all $s,t,u$.% The number of free variables equals the number of columns of $A$ minus $r(A)$% ; that is, $5-3=2$. \par Since the system is consistent and there are two free variables, % therefore the system has infinitely many solutions. \par Moreover, we now know quite a bit about how the solution will look. The % solution will be a two dimensional object in five dimensions ($ bR^{5}$), and% will have the form \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{bmatrix}x_{1}\ x_{2}\ x_{3}\ x_{4}\ x_{5}\end{bmatrix}=\underbrace{ egin{bmatrix}*\ *\ *\ *\ *\end{bmatrix}}_{\mathclap{	ext{Particular solution}}}+\overbrace{x_{2} egin% {bmatrix}*\ *\ *\ *\ *\end{bmatrix}+x_{5} egin{bmatrix}*\ *\ *\ *\ *\end{bmatrix}}^{\mathclap{	ext{Solution to the homogeneous equation}}}$ This is because there are two free variables and five variables in total. \par \par Let us look at this example with actual values in place of the % variables $s,t,u$: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[ccccc|r]1&0&0&0&0&7\ 0&0&1&0&1&3\ 0&0&0&1&0&-2\end{matrix}ight]\longrightarrow\left\{ egin{aligned}% \displaystyle x_{1}&\displaystyle+&\displaystyle 0x_{2}&\displaystyle+&% \displaystyle 0x_{3}&\displaystyle+&\displaystyle 0x_{4}&\displaystyle+&% \displaystyle 0x_{5}&\displaystyle=&\displaystyle 7\ &&&&\displaystyle x_{3}&\displaystyle+&&&\displaystyle x_{5}&\displaystyle=&% \displaystyle 3\ &&&&&&\displaystyle x_{4}&&&\displaystyle=&\displaystyle-2\end{aligned}ight.% $ \par The system tells us that $x_{3}=5-x_{5}$. Writing the solution in vector% form, we obtain \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{bmatrix}x_{1}\ x_{2}\ x_{3}\ x_{4}\ x_{5}\end{bmatrix}= egin{bmatrix}7\ x_{2}\ 3-x_{5}\ -2\ x_{5}\end{bmatrix}= egin{bmatrix}7\ 0\ 3\ -2\ 0\end{bmatrix}+x_{2} egin{bmatrix}0\ 1\ 0\ 0\ 0\end{bmatrix}+x_{5} egin{bmatrix}0\ 0\ -1\ 0\ 1\end{bmatrix}$ \par Thus there are infinitely many solutions, and the vector $ egin{bmatrix% }[r]7\ 0\ 3\ -2\ 0\end{bmatrix}$ represents one particular solution to the system. \par Here is an important observation: \par If we examine the last part of the solution we have found, plugging in % the two vectors $ egin{bmatrix}0\ 1\ 0\ 0\ 0\end{bmatrix}, egin{bmatrix}[r]0\ 0\ -1\ 0\ 1\end{bmatrix}$ into the system, then the result is zeroes: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle x_{2} egin{bmatrix}0\ 1\ 0\ 0\ 0\end{bmatrix}+x_{5} egin{bmatrix}[r]0\ 0\ -1\ 0\ 1\end{bmatrix}$&$$&$\displaystyle\left\{ egin{aligned}\displaystyle x_{1}&&&&% &&&&&\displaystyle=&\displaystyle 0\ &&&&\displaystyle x_{3}&\displaystyle+&&&\displaystyle x_{5}&\displaystyle=&% \displaystyle 0\ &&&&&&\displaystyle x_{4}&&&\displaystyle=&\displaystyle 0\end{aligned}ight.% $ \par \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{bmatrix}x_{1}\ x_{2}\ x_{3}\ x_{4}\ x_{5}\end{bmatrix}= egin{bmatrix}7\ x_{2}\ 3-x_{5}\ -2\ x_{5}\end{bmatrix}= egin{bmatrix}7\ 0\ 3\ -2\ 0\end{bmatrix}+\overbrace{x_{2}\underbrace{ egin{bmatrix}0\ 1\ 0\ 0\ 0\end{bmatrix}}_{v_{1}}+x_{5}\underbrace{ egin{bmatrix}[r]0\ 0\ -1\ 0\ 1\end{bmatrix}}_{v_{2}}}^{\mathclap{	ext{Homogenous solutions}}}$ \par The solution being in this form should remind us of the form of a plane.% In fact, this is the equation of a two dimensional plane within five % dimensions. We might draw it as \par  egin{figure}[H] \centering	ikzpicture  oreach\y/ \c{i}n {0/yellow} { \draw[fill=\c{]} (0,0+\y) to (1,1+\y) to (4,2+\y) to (3,1+\y) to (0,0+\y); \draw[->,>=triangle 60,thick] (0,0+\y) to (1,1+\y); \draw[->,>=triangle 60,thick] (0,0+\y) to (3,1+\y); \par 
