ode[blk] at (0,2) {}; \par \draw[dashed] (0,0) to (0,2); \@add@centering\end{figure} \par One may wonder whether a (consistent) linear system can have infinitely % many solutions and no free variables. The answer is no because there will only% be a particular solution. \par \@@section{paragraph}{Sx2.SS0.SSS0.Px4}{}{}{}{Question:}Does the % existence of a free variable guarantee infinitely many solutions? \par Consider the matrix \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[cccc|c]1&0&0&0&1\ 0&0&0&0&2\end{matrix}ight]$ Note that the second, third, and fourth columns have all zero entries, and so % they represent free variables. However, the second row indicates that the % system is inconsistent because a pivot has entered the constant column. \par \par \@@section{section}{Sx3}{}{}{}{Linear Span} \par Suppose we wish to `travel' in $ bR^{2}$ from the origin. What points % can we reach? Suppose we can only move along a certain vector, $v_{1}$:  egin{figure}[H] \centering\subfigure[b]{.45} \@@amsalign$\displaystyle v_{1}= egin{bmatrix}1\ 0\end{bmatrix}$\ $$\ $$ \subfigure[b]{.45} 	ikzpicture 
